'''脏话罐'''（{{lang|en|swear jar}}），是一种避免人们讲[[髒話|髒話]]的物品<ref>{{cite web |url=http://education.byu.edu/youcandothis/swearing_bad_language.html |title=Swearing and Bad Language |publisher=education.byu.edu |date= |accessdate=2014-06-10 |archive-date=2021-02-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210224195321/https://education.byu.edu/youcandothis/swearing_bad_language.html |dead-url=no }}</ref>。每次有人讲脏话时，旁人便会要求讲脏话者在罐中放一些钱当作[[罰金|罰金]]<ref name=Panorama>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/panorama/hi/front_page/newsid_7852000/7852305.stm|title=Panorama Archive: Dimbleby's swear-box|author=|date=2017-11-14|publisher=|accessdate=2017-11-14|via=www.bbc.co.uk|archive-date=2020-04-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200430213103/http://www.bbc.co.uk/panorama/hi/front_page/newsid_7852000/7852305.stm|dead-url=no}}</ref>。脏话罐可以是玻璃、瓷器或金属制成的，也可以带有一个有窄缝的盖子。罐中积累的钱可以用于事先约定的用途，也可以捐给[[慈善组织|慈善组织]]。

脏话罐的概念大约起源于19世纪90年代，当时名为“swear box”<ref>''Forest and Stream'', [March 20, 1890 https://www.google.com/books/edition/Forest_and_Stream/hEchAQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22swear%20box%22&pg=PA176&printsec=frontcover&bsq=%22swear%20box%22]</ref><ref>Thomas J. Henry, ''Claude Garton: A Story of Dunburgh University'', 1897, [https://www.google.com/books/edition/Claude_Garton/ZFJEAQAAMAAJ?hl=en&gbpv=1&dq=%22swear%20box%22&pg=PA167&printsec=frontcover&bsq=%22swear%20box%22 p. 167]</ref>，在20世纪10年代开始流行起来<ref name="ng">[https://books.google.com/ngrams/graph?content=swear+box%3Aeng_us_2012%2Cswear+jar%3Aeng_us_2012%2Cswear+box%3Aeng_gb_2012%2Cswear+jar%3Aeng_gb_2012&year_start=1850&year_end=2008&corpus=15&smoothing=3&share=&direct_url=t1%3B%2Cswear%20box%3Aeng_us_2012%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cswear%20jar%3Aeng_us_2012%3B%2Cc0%3B.t1%3B%2Cswear%20box%3Aeng_gb_2012%3B%2Cc0 Google nGrams comparison of swear box and swear jar in the US and in GB]</ref>。“swear jar”这一词语大约出现于20世纪80年代的美国，在英国没有记载<ref name="ng"/>；1988年美国电影《{{tsl|en|Moving (1988 film)|大搬家}}》中就有人提到过“swear jar”。在20世纪80年代，脏话罐的概念的概念便已非常流行<ref name="ng"/>。

